'''Hal Borne''' (December 26, 1911, [[Chicago]], Illinois - February 25, 2000, [[Tarzana, Los Angeles|Tarzana]], California) was an American popular song [[composer]], [[orchestra]] leader, [[music arranger]] and [[musical director]], who studied music at the [[University of Illinois]]. He wrote most frequently with the lyricists [[Sid Kuller]] and [[Ray Golden]], including songs for the [[Marx Brothers]] ("Sing While You Sell") and [[Tony Martin (entertainer)|Tony Martin]] ("Tenement Symphony").

At the beginning of his career he worked for [[RKO]] studios as the [[rehearsal]] [[pianist]] for [[Fred Astaire]]. In 1941 he collaborated with [[Duke Ellington]], [[Paul Francis Webster]] and Kuller on the progressive all-black revue ''[[Jump for Joy (1941 revue)|Jump for Joy]]'' which was supported by many [[Hollywood]] liberals of the time, such as [[Groucho Marx]], [[Mickey Rooney]] and [[Orson Welles]]. Borne became a big-band orchestra leader and in February 1942 signed as the music director for RCM's [[soundies]] (musical shorts filmed for [[jukeboxes]]) for which his trio often provided backings.<ref>''Billboard, February 28, 1942.</ref> For many years Borne was associated with Tony Martin and became his regular music director for live appearances throughout the 1950s and 60s.

Borne joined [[ASCAP]] in 1942 and was one of the composers for [[Ray Golden]]'s 1950 revue [[Alive and Kicking (musical)|Alive and Kicking]], featuring [[Jack Cassidy]], [[Bobby Van (actor)|Bobby Van]] and [[Carl Reiner]] and the debut of [[Gwen Verdon]]. In 1963 he composed most of the songs for the infamous first topless mainstream movie ''[[Promises! Promises!]]'', starring [[Jayne Mansfield]] and [[Marie McDonald|Marie ''(the Body)'' McDonald]] -- not to be confused with the subsequent [[Neil Simon]], [[Burt Bacharach]] musical ''[[Promises, Promises (musical)|Promises, Promises]]''.

He was celebrated for his piano improvisations and often jammed in duets with Ellington on the [[spinet]].<ref>Lax, David, ''One Man Show'', Washington Irving Gallery, 1976, p. 158</ref> Among his many albums, he supported Marie McDonald for her 1957 musical foray ''"The Body Sings"''. In Hollywood Borne worked on some famous [[Swing music|swing]] arrangements of [[Jerome Kern]] and [[Irving Berlin]] standards and claims to have come up with the well-known musical refrain "dah-dah-dee" to the line of [[Cheek to Cheek|"Heaven - I'm in heaven"]] in the 1935 film [[Top Hat]].<ref>Croce, Arlen, ''The Fred Astaire and Ginger Rogers Book'', Outerbridge & Lazard, 1972, p. 67 ISBN 0-88365-099-1</ref>

